Abstract: The choice of exchange rate regime is considered for a small open economy. Assuming
that different forms of fixed exchange rate regimes involve different costs of reneging, it
is shown that one potential beneficial aspect of joining a monetary union with a common
currency is that it is less likely to be exposed to ''speculative attacks'' than less formalized
fixed exchange rate arrangements.
