Title: Can Nominal Wage and Price Rigidities Be Equivalent Propagation Mechanisms?
The Case of Open Economics
Author-Name: Bo William Hansen
Author-Name: Lars Mayland Nielsen
Author-Email: lmn@nationalbanken.dk
Author-WorkPlace-Name: The National Bank of Denmark
Author-WorkPlace-Postal: Havnegade 5, 1093 Copenhagen K, Denmark
Author-WorkPlace-Fax: +45 3363 63 63
Abstract: Does it matter for the propagation mechanism following nominal shocks whether nominal
rigidities are specified as sticky wages instead of sticky prices? We analyze the question in a
standard dynamic general equilibrium "new open macro-economy" model, which is solved
analytically. By comparing the adjustment patterns of the terms of trade, in an otherwise
unchanged model under, respectively, nominal wage and price rigidities, we find that the two
types of rigidities give rise to the same persistence pattern. Specifically, nominal wage and
price rigidities are equivalent "impact adjusted" propagation mechanisms. Results are
presented for one-period nominal rigidities and two-period nominal staggering.
Classification-JEL: E32, F41
Keywords: Nominal shocks; nominal rigidities; propagation; persistence; staggering
